<body>
<segment id="1" parent="1001" relname="preparation">Richard</segment>
<segment id="2" parent="1002" relname="span">Herbert</segment>
<segment id="3" parent="2" relname="elaboration">( died 1510 )</segment>
<segment id="4" parent="1004" relname="same_unit">For other people of this name ,</segment>
<segment id="5" parent="1004" relname="same_unit">see Richard Herbert .</segment>
<segment id="6" parent="1007" relname="span">Arms of Herbert :</segment>
<segment id="7" parent="6" relname="elaboration">Per pale azure and gules , three lions rampant argent</segment>
<segment id="8" parent="1009" relname="span">Sir Richard Herbert Kt</segment>
<segment id="9" parent="1010" relname="span">( died 1510 )</segment>
<segment id="10" parent="9" relname="elaboration">of Ewyas , Herefordshire ,</segment>
<segment id="11" parent="1008" relname="same_unit">was an English knight , gentleman , landowner , and courtier .</segment>
<segment id="12" parent="1014" relname="span">He was an illegitimate son of William Herbert , 1st Earl of Pembroke , and Maud , a daughter of Adam ap Howell Graunt</segment>
<segment id="13" parent="12" relname="elaboration">( Gwynn ) .</segment>
<segment id="14" parent="1014" relname="evidence">[ 1 ]</segment>
<segment id="15" parent="1015" relname="joint">[ 2 ]</segment>
<segment id="16" parent="1015" relname="joint">[ 3 ]</segment>
<segment id="17" parent="1018" relname="span">Richard had a full brother</segment>
<segment id="18" parent="17" relname="elaboration">named George .</segment>
<segment id="19" parent="1018" relname="evidence">[ 3 ]</segment>
<segment id="20" parent="1020" relname="span">Richard Herbert of Ewyas should not be confused with his uncle , Sir Richard Herbert of Coldbrook , a brother of his father , William Herbert , 1st Earl of Pembroke .</segment>
<segment id="21" parent="20" relname="evidence">[ 4 ]</segment>
<segment id="22" parent="1022" relname="preparation">Herbert legacy</segment>
<segment id="23" parent="1024" relname="span">The titles and estates of the Earl of Pembroke descended to Herbert &apos;s younger , legitimate half-brother William ,</segment>
<segment id="24" parent="23" relname="evidence">[ 3 ]</segment>
<segment id="25" parent="1025" relname="span">but he achieved notability through his own merit and through his descendants :</segment>
<segment id="26" parent="1026" relname="span">&quot; Sir Richard Herbert , of Ewyas ,</segment>
<segment id="27" parent="1027" relname="span">who , though illegitimate , is ancestor of the men</segment>
<segment id="28" parent="27" relname="elaboration">who have really , in modern times , rendered the name of Herbert illustrious .</segment>
<segment id="29" parent="1029" relname="span">&quot;</segment>
<segment id="30" parent="29" relname="evidence">[ 5 ]</segment>
<segment id="31" parent="1031" relname="span">In 1465 , Richard Herbert was granted Westminster , manors of Grove , Radnore , Mookas , Brutescourt , Throuckeston , Westhide , Egelton , Redehire , Howton and Wormeton Tirell , in Herefordshire .</segment>
<segment id="32" parent="31" relname="evidence">[ 6 ]</segment>
<segment id="33" parent="1034" relname="joint">He was successful as a Gentleman Usher to King Henry VII</segment>
<segment id="34" parent="1035" relname="span">and was appointed Constable and Porter of Abergavenny Castle on 22 July 1509 .</segment>
<segment id="35" parent="34" relname="evidence">[ 3 ]</segment>
<segment id="36" parent="1034" relname="evidence">[ 4 ]</segment>
<segment id="37" parent="1037" relname="span">While Herbert is most often named as &quot; Sir Richard Herbert , &quot;</segment>
<segment id="38" parent="1038" relname="span">there is uncertainty</segment>
<segment id="39" parent="38" relname="circumstance">as to whether he was knighted .</segment>
<segment id="40" parent="1040" relname="span">In &quot;</segment>
<segment id="41" parent="1041" relname="same_unit">The Knights of England &quot; ,</segment>
<segment id="42" parent="1042" relname="contrast">there is a record of a Richard Herbert being knighted in 1513 ,</segment>
<segment id="43" parent="1043" relname="span">but that was three years after this man &apos;s death .</segment>
<segment id="44" parent="43" relname="evidence">[ 7 ]</segment>
<segment id="45" parent="1045" relname="contrast">According to Sil , Richard was never knighted ,</segment>
<segment id="46" parent="1046" relname="span">but was an Esquire .</segment>
<segment id="47" parent="46" relname="evidence">[ 3 ]</segment>
<segment id="48" parent="1048" relname="span">Richard is entitled Esquire in 1465 ,</segment>
<segment id="49" parent="1049" relname="span">when he was granted manors and lands .</segment>
<segment id="50" parent="49" relname="evidence">[ 6 ]</segment>
<segment id="51" parent="1055" relname="span">However , other sources</segment>
<segment id="52" parent="51" relname="evidence">[ 1 ]</segment>
<segment id="53" parent="1056" relname="joint">[ 2 ]</segment>
<segment id="54" parent="1056" relname="joint">[ 4 ]</segment>
<segment id="55" parent="1054" relname="evidence">[ 5 ]</segment>
<segment id="56" parent="1052" relname="same_unit">call him &quot; Sir Richard Herbert &quot; ,</segment>
<segment id="57" parent="1058" relname="span">and an article</segment>
<segment id="58" parent="59" relname="attribution">entitled &quot; The Family of Herbert &quot; in The Gentleman &apos;s Magazine states</segment>
<segment id="59" parent="1059" relname="span">that he was knighted by King Henry VIII ,</segment>
<segment id="60" parent="1060" relname="span">[ 8 ]</segment>
<segment id="61" parent="1061" relname="span">in which case</segment>
<segment id="62" parent="1062" relname="span">as he died in 1510 he would have been knighted in the last year of his life , and the first year of Henry VIII &apos;s reign ,</segment>
<segment id="63" parent="62" relname="elaboration">which began in 1509 .</segment>
<segment id="64" parent="1064" relname="preparation">Marriage</segment>
<segment id="65" parent="1067" relname="span">Richard married Margaret , a daughter of Sir Matthew Cradock of Swansea and of Alice</segment>
<segment id="66" parent="65" relname="elaboration">( or Jane )</segment>
<segment id="67" parent="1066" relname="same_unit">Mancell , widow of John Malefant .</segment>
<segment id="68" parent="1066" relname="evidence">[ 1 ]</segment>
<segment id="69" parent="1070" relname="span">Sir Matthew Cradock was receiver of Glamorgan ,</segment>
<segment id="70" parent="69" relname="evidence">[ 3 ]</segment>
<segment id="71" parent="1071" relname="span">through whom Castleston Castle passed to his daughter Margaret and Richard Herbert .</segment>
<segment id="72" parent="71" relname="evidence">[ 9 ]</segment>
<segment id="73" parent="1073" relname="span">Issue</segment>
<segment id="74" parent="1074" relname="span">Richard and Margaret Herbert had three surviving sons ,</segment>
<segment id="75" parent="1077" relname="span">one of whom was William Herbert , 1st Earl of Pembroke ,</segment>
<segment id="76" parent="75" relname="elaboration">who became the 1st Earl of Pembroke of the second creation</segment>
<segment id="77" parent="1077" relname="evidence">[ 5 ]</segment>
<segment id="78" parent="1078" relname="span">on 11 October 1551 .</segment>
<segment id="79" parent="78" relname="evidence">[ 3 ]</segment>
<segment id="80" parent="1082" relname="span">Later Earls of Pembroke</segment>
<segment id="81" parent="80" relname="evidence">[ 2 ] and Montgomery , and of Carnarvon , and the Dukes of Powis , of Pool Castle</segment>
<segment id="82" parent="1082" relname="elaboration">( extinct 1747 ) ,</segment>
<segment id="83" parent="1080" relname="same_unit">descend from Sir Richard Herbert .</segment>
<segment id="84" parent="1084" relname="span">Through a female line the Marquis of Bute derives his Glamorganshire estates .</segment>
<segment id="85" parent="84" relname="evidence">[ 5 ]</segment>
<segment id="86" parent="1085" relname="sequence">Herbert &apos;s son William married Anne Parr , sister of Queen Catherine Parr , the sixth and last wife of Henry VIII .</segment>
<segment id="87" parent="1087" relname="span">William served Henry VIII in many capacities ,</segment>
<segment id="88" parent="87" relname="elaboration">including Chief Gentleman of the Privy Chamber , Privy Councillor , and Receiver of the King &apos;s revenues .</segment>
<segment id="89" parent="1090" relname="sequence">He was knighted in 1544</segment>
<segment id="90" parent="1090" relname="sequence">and later appointed a Knight of the Garter .</segment>
<segment id="91" parent="1090" relname="evidence">[ 4 ]</segment>
<segment id="92" parent="1093" relname="span">Another son was Sir George Herbert of Swansea ,</segment>
<segment id="93" parent="92" relname="evidence">[ 10 ]</segment>
<segment id="94" parent="1094" relname="span">who was ancestor of the Herberts of Swansea , Cogan , Cookham , and the White Friars ,</segment>
<segment id="95" parent="94" relname="elaboration">who became extinct in 1739 .</segment>
<segment id="96" parent="1096" relname="span">Candleston Castle passed from Richard and Margaret to their son George .</segment>
<segment id="97" parent="96" relname="evidence">[ 9 ]</segment>
<segment id="98" parent="1098" relname="span">Richard was also the father of the illegitimate Herberts of Dinas Powis and Hengastell .</segment>
<segment id="99" parent="98" relname="evidence">[ 11 ]</segment>
<segment id="100" parent="1100" relname="preparation">Death</segment>
<segment id="101" parent="1100" relname="joint">Richard Herbert died between 2 and 12 September 1510</segment>
<segment id="102" parent="1100" relname="joint">and was buried in Abergavenny Church ;</segment>
<segment id="103" parent="1103" relname="span">his tomb has a lavishly decorated wall arch and an alabaster effigy .</segment>
<segment id="104" parent="103" relname="evidence">[ 1 ]</segment>
<segment id="105" parent="1103" relname="evidence">[ 12 ]</segment>
